Posted @withregram ‚Ä¢ @cosmoindia ‚ú®NEW ISSUE ANNOUNCEMENT ‚ú®Cosmo India‚Äôs new issue is here, featuring coverstars actor Vicky Kaushal and model Priyadarshini Chatterjee. Read excerpts of our exclusive chat with Vicky, where he tells us about his 'biggest' achievement so far, and why he never mulls over any decision. Catch his full interview in the new issue of Cosmopolitan India that will be available for you to download free, very soon ( watch this space!) 
.
Cosmo India: Did you always want to be an actor? Vicky Kaushal: ‚ÄúI think, subconsciously, it was always there. Because, even as a shy child, I would participate in all dance performances and stage shows. I really enjoyed that. Otherwise, I was so reserved, that no-one had even heard my voice! But on stage, I felt liberated. It gave me the chance to express myself, to have fun...‚Äù
.C: What are you most proud of?VK: ‚ÄúThe fact that my parents are proud of me. I don‚Äôt know how to put it, but there are moments that you know are extraordinary, but they become even more special when you see the happiness in your parents‚Äô eyes. Like, coincidentally, I won the National Award on this day last year. I was ecstatic! But when I saw my parents‚Äîand what it meant to them‚Äîthat was something else. Their reaction took the experience to another level for me.‚Äù

‚ÄòManmarziyaan‚Äô- The last scene between Vicky and Rumi in the film. Me and @taapsee (Happy Birthday! üòò) were ready in costumes chilling on this charpai, the dop was told to set the shots a certain way and he was set and this is when  @anuragkashyap10 takes a corner with his pad and pen to write the dialogues of the scene while @kanika.d is going üò±üßêüôÉ. We get the scene, rehearse and in a few minutes we start shooting. As per the written scene, the scene is supposed to end with our hug. As we hug with tears in our eyes, Anurag Sir comes in my eyeline behind the camera and starts miming me to break the hug... all this, while the shot is still rolling. I break the hug and AK doesn‚Äôt say ‚Äúcut‚Äù for a good long minute. The scene on the script is over. Me and Taapsee both don‚Äôt know what to do. Feeling awkward in the moment I start beat boxing and Taapsee smiles and we both end up chuckling. AK says cut and comes dancing in the room saying ‚ÄúMujhe mera breakup scene mil gaya!‚Äù This picture was taken right after we shot that Scene.

Your helmets, your gears, your guns... you hold on to, like your life depends on them. This was one army rule we all strictly lived by, through the Shoot of the Film. Once in costume, each and every one of us was responsible for our own gears. You wear them or hold them, it‚Äôs going to be with you through the span of the Shoot for that day. Our pockets would be full of protein bars, nuts and bags with bottles of energy drinks, because deep in those jungles sometimes no food trolleys or spot team were allowed to reach. Somedays I would wake up with my right index finger already bent imitating to pull the trigger. Those night shoots full of intense action, ofcourse were peppered with some fun banter and laughs in between shots amongst the boys, where our director @adityadharfilms would also join us. All of this feels worth it, with the generous love the Film is getting from you all. We thank you from the bottom of our hearts for keeping the Josh so high.

#Repost ‚ÄúDuring college, I decided to interview for an IT job just for the thrill of it. I wanted to experience the ‚Äònervousness‚Äô‚Äìwearing a tie & showing your resum√©. I already knew that I wasn‚Äôt going into that profession, even when I got a job offer. My dad‚Äôs an action director & despite his hope that ‚ÄòKaushal parivar ka chirag‚Äô will get a 9-5 job with stability‚Äî I announced that I wanted to be an actor. But, I didn‚Äôt know struggle like my father had. 
He went into films to survive. When my mom married him - they lived in a small room, with a chattai & a chair. My father built everything from there. It wasn‚Äôt easy - he had to hunt for our next meal. So he made sure to let us know where each piece of furniture came from. 
That‚Äôs why when I told him I wanted to act - he said be sure. Acting as a profession couldn‚Äôt be a ‚Äò?‚Äô for me. I needed to put 120% & not have a back up waiting. So I tore up that offer letter from the job & set out for auditions.
My 1st one was horrifying. It was for a small role & I realised how far from everything I was. On my way home, I was like ‚ÄòVicky, ab toh tune job letter bhi phaad diya!‚Äô
I was afraid, but I literally couldn‚Äôt give up. So the next day, I set off to more auditions. I even started theatre & evolved as an actor. I wanted to learn the practicality. Finally Masaan released in 2015. That‚Äôs when my dad saw my performance on a big screen. He was so proud- when he got a phone call from a friend - saying ‚ÄòVicky ke papa‚Äô He called me in 10 mins boasting ‚Äòyou know what happened? Someone called me Vicky‚Äôs dad today!‚Äô
So that‚Äôs it. The journey from being my father‚Äôs son to him being Vicky‚Äôs dad was what gave me hope‚Ä¶ things were changing. My happiest moment since then was when I 1st bought a car with my own money. When you‚Äôre younger, you say things like ‚ÄòI‚Äôll have my own Mercedes someday!‚Äô Never knowing when it‚Äôll happen. 
So I took my mom to the show room & she said - 'you remember when you were younger, you used to point out toy cars in shops? And today you‚Äôre making me sit in your car.‚Äô
She had teary eyes.That‚Äôs the moment I knew that I‚Äôve retained my title as being the ‚ÄòKaushal parivar ka chirag‚Äô & I did it on my own terms."

Found this while cleaning up my drawers today. My first time on a film set (Fiza) and the reason was to see this phenomena in flesh and blood. Someone told me that he only meets kids who can dance on 'Ek pal ka jeena' (obviously I was getting fooled), but I believed that and rehearsed and practiced dancing on the song for 3 days before meeting him. When I finally met, he was the sweetest person ever. Probably the only time I have stared at another human being for hours at stretch... coz may be for me he was not just a purush, he was a mahapurush. Inspiration... then, now and forever.
